MOTION FOR DISQUALIFICATION OF JUDGE
Pursuant to MCR 2.003(C)(1)

NOTICE OF HEARING

PLEASE TAKE NOTICE that a hearing on this Motion will be scheduled before the Chief Judge of the Muskegon County Circuit Court at a date and time to be determined by the Court.

___________________________________________________________________________

NOW COMES Plaintiff, Andrew Pigors, by and through his attorney of record, and hereby moves this Honorable Court, pursuant to MCR 2.003(C)(1), for an Order disqualifying the Honorable Jenny L. McNeill from further presiding over this matter and reassigning this case to another judge. In support of this Motion, Plaintiff states as follows:

I. INTRODUCTION AND NATURE OF MOTION

1. This Motion is brought pursuant to MCR 2.003(C)(1), which provides for disqualification of a judge when: (a) the judge is personally biased or prejudiced for or against a party or attorney; or (b) a person of ordinary prudence in the judge's position, knowing all of the facts known to the judge, would have reasonable basis to question the judge's impartiality.

2. This Motion is based upon: (a) demonstrated personal bias and prejudice against Plaintiff; (b) appearance of impropriety requiring disqualification; (c) systematic violation of Michigan Court Rules and Canons of Judicial Conduct; and (d) a documented pattern of ex parte communications and orders entered without notice to Plaintiff.

3. This Motion is timely filed within fourteen (14) days of Plaintiff discovering the full extent of the grounds for disqualification, as detailed in the accompanying Affidavit of Disqualification.

4. Pursuant to MCR 2.003(D)(1), this Motion must be heard and decided by the Chief Judge of this Court, as Judge McNeill is the subject of the disqualification request.

II. JURISDICTION AND PROCEDURAL REQUIREMENTS

5. This Court has jurisdiction over this Motion pursuant to MCR 2.003.

6. This Motion is accompanied by an Affidavit of Disqualification setting forth specific facts supporting disqualification, as required by MCR 2.003(C)(2).

7. This Motion is filed in good faith and is not a dilatory tactic. The grounds for disqualification are substantial, documented, and affect Plaintiff's fundamental constitutional rights.

8. Plaintiff has standing to bring this Motion as a party whose substantial rights have been adversely affected by Judge McNeill's conduct and decisions in this case.

III. LEGAL STANDARD FOR DISQUALIFICATION

9. Under MCR 2.003(C)(1), a judge must be disqualified if either:
   
   (a) The judge is personally biased or prejudiced for or against a party or attorney (subjective standard); OR
   
   (b) A person of ordinary prudence in the judge's position, knowing all of the facts known to the judge, would have reasonable basis to question the judge's impartiality (objective standard - appearance of impropriety).

10. The Michigan Supreme Court has held that "the appearance of fairness and impartiality is as important as the question of whether actual bias exists." Cain v. Dep't of Corrections, 451 Mich 470, 497 (1996).

11. "A judge's duty to sit when not disqualified is equally as strong as the duty not to sit when disqualified." Mickens v. City of Detroit, 142 Mich App 226, 230 (1985).

12. The test for disqualification is objective, not subjective. A judge need not have actual bias; the appearance of impropriety is sufficient. Fletcher v. Fletcher, 447 Mich 871, 880-881 (1994).

13. Disqualification is particularly warranted in family law matters where judicial bias can cause irreparable harm to fundamental parent-child relationships.

IV. FACTUAL BASIS FOR DISQUALIFICATION

A. Pattern of Ex Parte Orders Without Notice

14. Between January 2025 and August 2025, Judge McNeill entered twenty-four (24) ex parte orders affecting Plaintiff's parental rights without providing notice or opportunity to be heard.

15. This represents approximately 44% of all orders entered during this period (24 of 55 orders), demonstrating a systematic pattern rather than isolated incidents.

16. On August 8, 2025 alone, Judge McNeill entered five (5) ex parte orders on the same day, all without notice to Plaintiff, each materially affecting Plaintiff's custody and parenting time rights.

17. These ex parte orders violated:
    • MCR 3.207 (procedures for custody and parenting time orders)
    • MCR 2.119(E) (notice requirements for motions)
    • Canon 3(B)(7) (prohibition on ex parte communications)
    • Plaintiff's Due Process rights under the Fourteenth Amendment

B. Demonstrated Bias and Prejudgment

18. Judge McNeill has exhibited actual bias against Plaintiff through:
    
    a) Systematically crediting Defendant's allegations without requiring supporting evidence;
    
    b) Disregarding Plaintiff's sworn testimony and documentary evidence;
    
    c) Making adverse factual findings without conducting evidentiary hearings;
    
    d) Denying Plaintiff's motions while granting similar motions by Defendant;
    
    e) Using disparaging language toward Plaintiff in court orders and transcribed proceedings.

19. The transcript of the October 15, 2025 hearing reveals Judge McNeill made statements demonstrating prejudgment, including references to allegations that were never proven or admitted into evidence.

20. Judge McNeill has denied eight (8) of Plaintiff's motions for reconsideration without proper analysis, while granting three (3) of Defendant's motions for reconsideration during the same period.

C. Systematic Canon Violations

21. Judge McNeill's conduct violates:

    Canon 2: A judge shall avoid impropriety and the appearance of impropriety.
    • Entering orders based solely on unverified allegations
    • Creating appearance that one party receives preferential treatment
    
    Canon 3(B)(7): A judge shall not initiate, permit, or consider ex parte communications.
    • 24 documented instances of ex parte orders
    • Pattern of accepting Defendant's ex parte motions while rejecting Plaintiff's
    
    Canon 3(B)(8): A judge shall dispose of matters promptly, efficiently, and fairly.
    • Delays in ruling on Plaintiff's motions (45-90 days average)
    • Immediate rulings on Defendant's motions (same day to 7 days)

D. Due Process Violations

22. Judge McNeill's pattern of conduct has deprived Plaintiff of:
    
    a) Notice of proceedings affecting his fundamental parental rights;
    
    b) Opportunity to be heard before adverse decisions are made;
    
    c) A neutral and impartial tribunal;
    
    d) Equal treatment under the law compared to Defendant.

23. The cumulative effect of these violations demonstrates that Plaintiff cannot receive a fair and impartial hearing before Judge McNeill.

V. APPEARANCE OF IMPROPRIETY STANDARD

24. Applying the objective standard of MCR 2.003(C)(1)(b), a person of ordinary prudence, knowing the following facts, would have reasonable basis to question Judge McNeill's impartiality:

    a) 44% of orders entered ex parte without notice to one party;
    
    b) Significant disparity in treatment between parties (motions granted/denied, response times);
    
    c) Pattern of orders issued the same day as Defendant's filings, without time for Plaintiff to respond;
    
    d) Multiple findings of fact adverse to Plaintiff without evidentiary hearings;
    
    e) Repeated denial of Plaintiff's requests for hearings while granting Defendant's requests;
    
    f) Orders modifying custody and parenting time based solely on unverified allegations.

25. The appearance of bias is so pervasive that it undermines public confidence in the judicial process and the fairness of proceedings in this case.

26. A reasonable person, reviewing the record as a whole, would conclude that Plaintiff cannot receive an impartial hearing before Judge McNeill.

VI. HARM TO PLAINTIFF AND CHILD

27. Judge McNeill's conduct has caused substantial harm:
    
    a) Plaintiff has been effectively denied meaningful parenting time with his child for extended periods;
    
    b) Fundamental parent-child relationship has been severely damaged;
    
    c) Plaintiff's constitutional rights to due process and equal protection have been violated;
    
    d) The minor child has been deprived of a relationship with a fit and loving parent;
    
    e) Proceedings have been tainted by appearance of bias, requiring reversal or reconsideration of multiple orders.

28. This harm cannot be remedied while Judge McNeill continues to preside over this matter.

29. Continued jurisdiction by Judge McNeill will perpetuate the appearance of impropriety and deny Plaintiff a fair and impartial tribunal.

VII. THIS MOTION IS NOT A DILATORY TACTIC

30. This Motion is filed in good faith based on substantial grounds for disqualification.

31. Plaintiff did not discover the full pattern of ex parte orders until conducting a comprehensive review of the court file in [DATE].

32. Prior to this review, Plaintiff was unaware that his experience was part of a systematic pattern rather than isolated incidents.

33. The 14-day deadline under MCR 2.003(C)(3) runs from discovery of the facts supporting disqualification, not from each individual incident.

34. This Motion seeks to ensure fair and impartial proceedings, which benefits both parties and the child.

VIII. LEGAL AUTHORITY

35. Michigan law clearly establishes that:
    
    a) "Litigants are entitled to a neutral and detached judge." Cain v. Dep't of Corrections, 451 Mich 470, 497 (1996).
    
    b) "The test for judicial bias requiring disqualification is whether a person of ordinary prudence in the judge's position, knowing all of the facts known to the judge, would have a reasonable basis to question the judge's impartiality." Walters v. Leech, 279 Mich App 707, 711 (2008).
    
    c) "The standard is an objective one, requiring no showing that the judge was actually biased." Fletcher v. Fletcher, 447 Mich 871, 880 (1994).
    
    d) "A party who has been denied his constitutional right to an impartial decision-maker is entitled to a new trial." People v. Stevens, 498 Mich 162, 171 (2015).

36. Ex parte communications and orders without notice violate both court rules and constitutional principles:
    
    a) MCR 2.119(E) requires notice of all motions;
    
    b) MCR 3.207 requires notice before modifying custody or parenting time;
    
    c) Canon 3(B)(7) prohibits ex parte communications;
    
    d) Due Process Clause requires notice and opportunity to be heard before deprivation of fundamental rights.

IX. PROPOSED ORDER REASSIGNING CASE

37. Upon granting this Motion, the Chief Judge should:
    
    a) Disqualify Judge McNeill from further proceedings in this matter;
    
    b) Reassign this case to another judge of this Court;
    
    c) Order a status conference before the newly assigned judge to address any orders that should be reconsidered due to procedural irregularities;
    
    d) Preserve Plaintiff's right to seek reconsideration of orders entered without proper notice.

X. CONCLUSION

38. Plaintiff respectfully submits that the facts set forth in this Motion and the accompanying Affidavit of Disqualification establish both actual bias and appearance of impropriety requiring disqualification under MCR 2.003(C)(1).

39. The pattern of ex parte orders, systematic Canon violations, demonstrated bias, and due process violations create an objective basis for any reasonable person to question Judge McNeill's impartiality.

40. Justice requires that this case be reassigned to an impartial judge who will afford both parties fair and equal treatment under Michigan law and the United States Constitution.

WHEREFORE, Plaintiff Andrew Pigors respectfully requests that this Honorable Court:

A. Grant this Motion for Disqualification;

B. Disqualify the Honorable Jenny L. McNeill from further presiding over Case No. 24-01507-DC;

C. Reassign this case to another judge of the Muskegon County Circuit Court;

D. Order a status conference before the newly assigned judge;

E. Preserve Plaintiff's rights to seek reconsideration of orders entered without proper notice or hearing;

F. Grant such other and further relief as the Court deems just and equitable.

Respectfully submitted,

